    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="1222"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1222">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/2903.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Mexican Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Translation.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexican Embassy</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington,
                                D. C.</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <lb/> [<date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-26">undated</date>] (Received
                        February 26, 1912—2.45 p.m.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have received telegraphic instructions from my Government to beg of you, as I
                    now have the honor to do, to be pleased to let me know what credit may be given
                    to the press report recently published that American troops are leaving for El
                    Paso with orders to cross into Mexican territory if shots are fired at the
                    American side from Ciudad Juárez or any other place.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilberto Crespo y Martinez</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
